# Ethernet Standards & Specifications (IEEE 802.3)

A comprehensive guide to standard Ethernet specifications, speeds, and media types for CCNA preparation.

---

## 1. Overview of IEEE 802.3
Ethernet is the most widely used local area network (LAN) technology. It operates at both the **Physical Layer (Layer 1)** and **Data Link Layer (Layer 2)** of the OSI model. The IEEE 802.3 standard defines the physical layer and the MAC (Media Access Control) sublayer of the data link layer for wired Ethernet.

---

## 2. Ethernet Naming Convention
Ethernet standards follow a specific naming syntax: **[Speed][Signaling Method][Media Type]**

* **Speed:** The data rate (e.g., `10` = 10 Mbps, `100` = 100 Mbps, `1000` = 1 Gbps).
* **Signaling Method:** Almost always `BASE` (Baseband), meaning the medium carries only one data signal at a time.
* **Media Type/Distance:** Indicates the cable type or maximum segment length (e.g., `T` = Twisted Pair, `SX`/`LX`/`ZX` = Fiber Optic).

---

## 3. Key Ethernet Standards Summary

| Standard Name | Common Name | IEEE Standard | Max Speed | Cable Type | Max Distance |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **10BASE-T** | Standard Ethernet | 802.3 | 10 Mbps | Cat3/Cat5 UTP | 100 meters |
| **100BASE-TX** | Fast Ethernet | 802.3u | 100 Mbps | Cat5 or better UTP | 100 meters |
| **1000BASE-T** | Gigabit Ethernet | 802.3ab | 1 Gbps (1000 Mbps)| Cat5e/Cat6 UTP | 100 meters |
| **10GBASE-T** | 10 Gigabit Ethernet| 802.3an | 10 Gbps | Cat6a/Cat7 UTP | 100 meters |
| **1000BASE-SX** | Gigabit Fiber (Short) | 802.3z | 1 Gbps | Multi-Mode Fiber (MMF) | ~550 meters |
| **1000BASE-LX** | Gigabit Fiber (Long) | 802.3z | 1 Gbps | Single-Mode Fiber (SMF) | ~5 kilometers |

